On September 26, 2009, the White House released a statement from Press Secretary Robert Gibbs regarding President Obama's calls to the FBI and NYPD. The President called into a counterterrorism briefing that the NYPD was giving to John Brennan, the President's counterterrorism and homeland security advisor. He thanked them for their outstanding work during the United Nations General Assembly and expressed his appreciation and admiration for their ongoing terrorism investigation. The President commended the exceptional teamwork between the NYPD, other police departments, and federal departments and agencies. He also expressed gratitude for the work being done by the Department of Justice and previously called FBI Director Mueller to thank him for the strong work of the Bureau. The President emphasized the need to maintain vigilance and continue strong investigative and intelligence work to protect the homeland from terrorist attacks.